aphy\n6. Urethrography\n7. Ultrasonography/Doppler\n8. CT\n9. MRI\n1- Kidney ureter bladder X-ray {KUB}\n▪ KUB is an X-ray to examine GUT system\n▪ Radio-density structures (ex.\nBones/stones) appear white\n▪ Radio lucent structures (ex. Tissues/fat)\nappear black\n• Advantages:\n▪ Initial modality to visualize calcifications\n& radio-opaque stones along urinary tract\n▪ Inexpensive\n▪ Available\n• Disadvantages:\n▪ Ionizing radiation exposure\n▪ No soft tissue details (no evaluation\nof backpressure changes)\nKUB is used to detect Stones:\nUrinary bladder stone\n1- Urinary bladder stone\nUreteric stone\n1. Radio-opaque=white\n2. Sharply defined\n3. At anatomical site of bladder\n4. Can be large\n2- Renal Stones\n1. At anatomical site of kidney\n2. Can be branching “staghorn”\n3- Ureteric Stones\n1. Along the course of ureter\n2. Smaller than renal stones\nRenal stone\n3. Oblong Ureteric stone\n118"}